===Etymology===
From Middle English '''spere''' < Old French '''espere''' < Latin [[sphaera]] (globe, ball, celestial sphere) < Greek {{IPAchar|[[σφαῖρα]]}} (ball, globe), of unknown origin.

===Noun===
'''sphere''' (''plural:'' '''[[spheres]]''')

#(''geometry'') The set of all points in [[three-dimensional]] [[Euclidean space]] (or {{n}}-dimensional space, in topology) that are a fixed distance from a fixed point.
#Any three-dimensional object every [[cross-section]] of which is a [[circle]].
#The region in which something or someone is active.

====Synonyms====
*(''in geometry''): [[3-sphere]] (''geometry''), [[2-sphere]] (''topology''); see [http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Sphere.html]
*(''object''): [[ball]], [[orb]]
*(''region of activity''): [[area]], [[domain]], [[field]]

